<TITLE> India to offer credit line for rail, infra projects in Bangladesh </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 bdnews24.com New Delhi Correspondent New Delhi, Jan 9 (bdnews24.com)  New Delhi is set to offer Dhaka credit line for several infrastructure and development projects in Bangladesh during prime minister Sheikh Hasina's visit, Indian officials say. Credit extended by New Delhi would be used in railway projects and for supply of locomotives, coaches and buses as well as other infrastructure projects in Bangladesh, sources in India's ministry of external affairs say. In addition, India will also lay a railway-link between Akhaura and Agartala, the capital of the northeastern Indian state of Tripura. The details of the bilateral cooperation in the railway sector are likely to be finalised when Indian railway minister Mamata Banerjee calls on Hasina on January 12 (Tuesday). Banerjee is also expected to be present when the Hasina holds delegation-level talks with her Indian counterpart Manmohan Singh at Hyderabad House in New Delhi on the 11th (Monday). India's finance minister Pranab Mukherjee and external affairs minister SM Krishna are also likely to be present in the delegation-level talks, which will be followed by signing of three security agreements on Mutual Legal Assistance on Criminal Matters, Transfer of Sentenced Persons and Combating International Terrorism, Organised Crime and Illicit Drug Trafficking. A Memorandum of Understanding for cooperation in the power sector will also be signed on the same occasion. New Delhi, sources said, is also ready to consider Dhaka's request for duty-free market access for 232 products from Bangladesh. A highly-placed official said that India had already removed 47 items from its negative list for the benefit of Bangladesh. To help Bangladesh improve the quality of products to be exported to India; New Delhi will also offer training to the officials of the Bangladesh Standard and Training Institute (BSTI). "We will help upgrade the BSTI certification procedure to make it sure that the Bangladeshi entrepreneurs do not face any problem while exporting their products to India or other countries," said a senior official of the Indian government. 
